'''Patrick McGuire''' is a Scottish [[solicitor]] and [[solicitor advocate]].<ref>{{cite news|title=HIV blood products inquiry to view new evidence|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-20299302|accessdate=28 April 2014|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=12 November 2012}}</ref> He is a partner with personal injury law firm [[Thompsons Solicitors]].<ref name=jo1>{{cite web|title=Re-formed Access to Justice Committee members confirmed|url=http://www.journalonline.co.uk/News/1010215.aspx|publisher=Journal of the [[Law Society of Scotland]]|date=13 September 2011|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>

He is known for his campaigning on issues relating to the rights of victims of accident and disease, including calling for and serving as the Recognised Legal Representative in three of the four [[Public inquiries]] held in Scotland since the [[Inquiries Act 2005]] came into force: the [[The ICL Inquiry|ICL / Stockline]] Public Inquiry;<ref>{{cite news|title=Senior judge to lead inquiry into fatal factory explosion|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/senior-judge-to-lead-inquiry-into-fatal-factory-explosion-1-702671|accessdate=28 April 2014|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=5 December 2007}}</ref> the Vale of Leven Hospital Public Inquiry ([[C difficile|C-difficile]]);<ref>{{cite news|last=Reporter|first=Staff|title=A leading lawyer says the results of an inquiry into a C. diff outbreak at the Vale of Leven Hospital must be applied across Scotland.|url=http://www.thecourier.co.uk/news/health/campaigners-say-vale-of-leven-c-diff-inquiry-must-result-in-national-action-1.55255|accessdate=28 April 2014|newspaper=[[The Courier (Dundee)|The Courier]]|date=23 August 2011}}</ref> and the Penrose Inquiry (infected blood products causing [[Hepatitis C]] and [[HIV]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=HIV blood products inquiry to view new evidence|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-20299302|accessdate=28 April 2014|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=12 November 2012}}</ref> Other victim-related campaigns include [[Poly Implant Prothèse|PiP breast implants]],<ref>{{cite journal|title=Thompsons takes up breast implants cause|journal=Journal of the [[Law Society of Scotland]]|date=9 January 2012|url=http://www.journalonline.co.uk/News/1010667.aspx|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref> [[2010 DePuy Hip Recall|Depuy hip replacements]],<ref>{{cite journal|title=Victims of dangerous hip implant defect could get compensation|journal=Journal of the [[Law Society of Scotland]]|date=2 December 2011|url=http://www.journalonline.co.uk/News/1010548.aspx|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref> cyclists injured as a result of Edinburgh’s tram works<ref>{{cite news|last=McCann|first=David|title=Edinburgh faces £1m tram payout to injured cyclists|url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/transport/edinburgh-faces-1m-tram-payout-to-injured-cyclists-1-2650601|accessdate=28 April 2014|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=22 November 2012}}</ref> and [[Edinburgh City Council]]’s handling of babies ashes at [[Mortonhall|MortonHall Crematorium]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Mortonhall baby ashes inquiry calls ‘unanswerable’|url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/mortonhall-baby-ashes-inquiry-calls-unanswerable-1-2909821|accessdate=28 April 2014|newspaper=[[Edinburgh Evening News]]|date=25 April 2013}}</ref>

In 2005 his work with trade unions on corporate homicide led to him being appointed as the [[Scottish Trades Union Congress|STUC]]'s legal adviser to the panel of experts set up by the [[Justice Minister]], [[Cathy Jamieson]], to consider the issue of [[Corporate Manslaughter and Corporate Homicide Act 2007|corporate killing in Scotland]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Understanding the Corporate Manslaughter and Corporate Homicide Act 2007 |publisher=Ministry of Justice |url=http://www.justice.gov.uk/docs/manslaughterhomicideact07.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=2007-10-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025031113/http://www.justice.gov.uk/docs/manslaughterhomicideact07.pdf |archivedate=25 October 2007 }}</ref>

More recently Patrick has been involved in campaigning for a review of the civil justice system in Scotland<ref>{{cite news|last=Alderson, Home affairs correspondent, BBC Scotland|first=Reevel|title=Civil court reforms to speed Scottish justice|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-26083425|accessdate=28 April 2014|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=7 February 2014}}</ref> and reform of Scotland’s [[Fatal accident inquiry|Fatal Accident Inquiry]] system.<ref>{{cite web|title=MSP Announces Fatal Accident Bill|url=http://www.patriciaferguson.labour.co.uk/msp-announces-fatal-accident-bill|publisher=www.labour.co.uk|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>

He also serves on the [[Law Society of Scotland]]’s ''Access to Justice Committee''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Re-formed Access to Justice Committee members confirmed|journal=Journal of the [[Law Society of Scotland]]|date=13 September 2011|url=http://www.journalonline.co.uk/News/1010215.aspx|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>

==Notable cases==
* Patrick Davidson v Lothian & Borders Fire Brigade, which established that, despite the need to ensure that [[fire-fighters]] are properly and fully trained, fire-fighters still have the same rights under the health and safety legislation as any other employee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Opinion of Lord Dawson|url=http://www.scotcourts.gov.uk/opinions/O630_5_97.html|publisher=[[Court of Session]]|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>
* Clement v [[Scottish Ambulance Service]] and Skinner v Scottish Ambulance Service, which established that use of traditional needles by branches of the NHS could be considered a breach of the country's health and safety legislation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Opinion of Lord Marnoch|url=http://www.scotcourts.gov.uk/opinions/A32403.html|publisher=[[Court of Session]]|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>

